# Git Commit Discipline

- Create commits only when the user explicitly asks for a commit.
- When the user asks for commits, make them atomic: one logical change per commit, with no unrelated files mixed in.
- "Atomic" means split by reviewable intent, not by the user's broad task. If one task contains separable concerns such as rule/doc updates, backend/API work, frontend UI, migrations, generated contracts, cleanup, or tests, create separate commits for the concerns that can stand alone.
- Do not bundle a full-stack feature into one commit just because it was implemented in one work session. Keep dependent generated artifacts with the source-of-truth change that produced them, and keep UI wiring separate when it can be reviewed independently.
- Stage only files that belong to the same change. Do not bundle cleanup, refactors, generated files, and feature work together unless they are inseparable parts of one logical change.
- Prefer small, reviewable commits with clear intent and commit messages in English that explain the purpose of the change.
- Follow the repository's existing commit message style unless the user asks for a different one.
- Do not mention Cursor in commit history. Do not add `Co-authored-by: Cursor <cursoragent@cursor.com>`, any other Cursor trailer, or any Cursor mention in the subject, body, or trailers of a commit message.
- After creating a commit, verify the final stored commit message. If the local environment injected a forbidden Cursor mention into an unpushed commit, rewrite that local commit before considering the task complete.
- Follow normal safe git workflow: inspect status/diff before committing, avoid destructive git operations, and do not rewrite published history unless the user explicitly asks.
- Do not push, force-push, or create remote side effects unless the user explicitly asks for that step.
